<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-912-008  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 912 008.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Nov 27 1989 v6 n47 p13(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Vendors postpone plans to offer 8514/A-compatible graphics cards.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bernard, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Western Digital Imaging (product introduction)ATI Technologies Inc. (product introduction)Matrox Electronic Systems Ltd. (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Compatible HardwareComputer graphicsGraphics Boards-CardsProduct IntroductionMarket EntryMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Diane BernardandM;Of the slew of vendors that promised to showcase 8514/A-compatible graphicsboards at Comdex/Fall earlier this month, just three announced new boards, asthe rest succumbed to a case of early-market jitters.andM;Western Digital Imaging, ATI Technologies Inc. and Matrox Electronics SystemsLtd. unveiled boards based on different 8514/A-clone chip sets that provideresolutions at least equal to the 1,024-by-768-pixel resolution of IBM's8514/A adapter, officials from the firms said.andP;  All three offerings will beavailable in the first quarter of 1990, they said.andM;Other firms, including Headland Technology Inc., STB Systems Inc. and SigmaDesigns Inc., shelved plans to announce new boards, weakening establishmentof IBM's 8514/A adapter as a high-resolution graphics standard.andM;Headland will not announce its board for two additional months because thefirm wants to launch both Micro Channel architecture (MCA) and ExtendedIndustry Standard Architecture (EISA) versions, said Marty Flock, director ofmarketing at the Fremont, Calif., firm.andM;Headland officials had said last summer that the firm would launch a $1,0008514/A-compatible controller that supports resolutions as high as 1,280 by1,024 pixels in non-interlaced mode.andM;Officials from STB Systems, who also said the firm would launch an 8514/Aboard at Comdex, declined to unveil a high-end graphics board until theysettled on 8514/A-clone chip sets, which are available from a variety ofvendors, that are 100 percent compatible with IBM's.andM;&quot;We're letting others throw fear, uncertainty and doubt into the market overwhether 8514/A clones are fully compatible,&quot; said Brett Berg, product managerat the Richardson, Texas, firm.andP;  STB plans to unveil the board at the end ofJanuary.andM;Sigma Designs has no such compatibility qualms, but held up its announcementof an 8514/A offering until the first quarter of next year because of ashortage of finished silicon for the chips, according to Ed Schaider, vicepresident of marketing at the Fremont, Calif., firm.andO;</TEXT></DOC>